arch:property.oc:show_val: Locus 19 extends the full length and width of Trench 85.

This coarse, compacted Strong Brown (Munsell 7.5 YR 5/8) fluvial layer is comparable to that found throughout the temple complex below the upper level of collapse. Primary inclusions include pottery, shell and bone and, to a lesser degree, plaster. Contained within this locus is a thin burn layer, Locus 20, which is thought to be a brief period of occupation during the extended period of accumulation of the fluvial material.
Extensive deposit of fluvial materials from the south- most likely following a period of major destruction and collapse in the rest of the temple.

Phase IX: Major CE 363 earthquake leads to the collapse of major temple architectural elements including the West Porch columns. Collapse and accumulation of debris around the temple east columns and on top of the lower risers of interior and rear staircases. Buckling of the west intercolumnar wall. Possible conflagration. Primary fluvial layer is deposited.
